## What is GitHub?

![github](https://static.javatpoint.com/tutorial/git/images/what-is-github.png)

  ###### - code hosting platform
 ###### - lets you (and others) work together on projects.

# GitHub essentials are :


## Repositories :
![Repositories](https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20191121165133/repository1.jpg)
 ###### - store your code and make changes to it.
 ###### - Your changes are tracked with version control.
 ###### - You can add files to a repository
   ###### - When you create a project.
   ###### - After you create a project.
 ###### - You can clone a repository.



## Branches
![Branches](https://uploads.sitepoint.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/1562127879155993571903-feature-branch-workflow.png)
 ###### - different versions of a repository at the same time.
 ###### - default Branche is "master".
 ###### - Any other branch is a copy of the master branch.
 ###### - When changes are ready >> can be merged into the master branch.



## Commits
![Commits](https://www.cybermundus.com/post/git-spoofing/MasterBranch.png)
 ###### - At GitHub, changes are called commits.
 ###### - command is used to save your changes to the local repository
 ###### - Each commit (change) has a description explaining why a change was made.
 ###### - what changes were made when and by who ?



## Pull Requests
![Pull Requests](https://opensource.com/sites/default/files/styles/image-full-size/public/lead-images/checklist_hands_team_collaboration.png?itok=u82QepPk)
 ###### - a feature that makes it easier for developers to collaborate.
 ###### - help keep changes separate from the main project .
 ###### - You make local code changes and then submit those changes to a remote project maintainer for review before those changes are implemented, or merged.